In class during Week 6, I spent too long covering the ‚Äúbase‚Äù DGP which generates Random Variables \(Y\) and \(E\), such that \(Y\) and \(E\) are statistically correlated despite ‚Äútruly‚Äù being independently-generated random values in \(\{0, 1\}\). Spent too long, meaning, we didn‚Äôt get to cover the case of the do-Calculus modified DGP, where we force \(E \leftarrow 1\) within the DGP itself, so that we could see how this ability to intervene in the DGP is what allows us to infer causation from correlation!
So, in this writeup, I‚Äôd like to write it out, so that rather than me trying to sprint through it on the board in the classroom, you can process it at your own pace üíÜ
